      <div xml:id="NA330-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi talaimakaṉai vāyiṉ maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante refused the door to HIM.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA330">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            taṭamarup perumaip piṟaḻcuva lirumpōttu</l>
<l>            maṭanaṭai nāraip palliṉa miriya</l>
<l>            neṭunīrt taṇkayan tuṭumeṉa pāyntu</l>
<l>            nāṭṭoḻil varuttam vīṭac cēṭciṉai</l>
<l>            yiruḷpuṉai maruti ṉiṉṉiḻal vatiyum</l>
<l>            yāṇa rūraniṉ māṇiḻai makaḷirai</l>
<l>            yemmaṉait tantunī taḻīiyiṉu mavartam</l>
<l>            puṉmaṉat tuṇmaiyō varitē yavarum</l>
<l>            paintoṭi makaḷiroṭu ciṟuvarp payantu</l>
<l>            naṉṟi cāṉṟa kaṟpō</l>
<l>            ṭempā ṭāta lataṉiṉu maritē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent4">        O man from the fertile village,</l>
<l>            where the dark male with irregular<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">piṟaḻ cuval</term>: the verb <term xml:lang="ta">piṟaḻ</term> is slightly surprising here, since elsewhere in the NA it is used several times of the leaping of the <term xml:lang="ta">Vāḷai</term> fish. So, if it is not meant to refer to the fact that the bull does not keep its neck steady, we might consider the less well-attested, but formulaic variant <term xml:lang="ta">piṇar cuval</term>: "rough-necked" (cf. NA 336.1).</note> nape of the broad-horned buffalo cow</l>
<l>        springs with a splash(?) into the cool pond of deep(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">neṭu nīr</term>: since this is the water of a pond or tank, <term xml:lang="ta">neṭu</term> can either refer to the water being deep, or, in a temporal extension, to the water being permanent.</note> water,</l>
<l rend="indent">            so that the many groups of herons with inexperienced(?) gait retreat,</l>
<l>        [and] stays in the pleasing shade of the Marutu tree decorated with dark,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            with lofty branches, to repell the suffering from the daily task,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            even if you bring to our house [and] embrace [there]</l>
<l rend="indent4">            your women with glorious jewels,</l>
<l>        as for sincerity(?), in their low minds, it [is] rare.</l>
<l>        Rarer than that is their<note place="foot">Presumably the <term xml:lang="ta">avarum</term> of line 8 has to be read as a genitive to <term xml:lang="ta">ātal</term>. But what is the meaning of um here? Any of them?</note> becoming of our propriety,</l>
<l rend="indent">            with fidelity worthy of kindness,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            bringing forth children with [the help of?] women with fresh bracelets.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
